actual.value:
- Background scoping paper has been developed;
- Based on the findings from the scoping paper and in response to the Covid-19 context, an activity plan devised for 2021 focusing on a number of targeted multi-stakeholder engagements, rather
than a single regional-level workshop as originally conceptualised.

target.value:
- An expert multi-stakeholder workshop (involving participants from government, businesses, civil society, academia, etc.) has been held at regional level to identify priority policy and practice actions to address the human rights implications of the digital transition in the Sub-Saharan African region;
- A policy briefing is published and disseminated that builds on the 2020 background paper and the expert multi-stakeholder workshop, documenting key recommendations for state, business and civil society actors to address the human rights implications of the digital transition in the region;
- Findings and recommendations have been presented in relevant regional or international fora.

- Capacity building and engagement with the state actors responsible for development of the NAP has been undertaken;
- Engagement with the Tanzanian National Commission for Human Rights and Good Governance to consolidate business and human rights priorities has been undertaken. including with focus on the business and human rights priorities going forward under the new Commissioners;
- A multi-stakeholder workshop with a select number of participants active in UNGPs implementation has been convened and specific aims and objectives for UNGPs implementation going forward have been identified based on the discussion.

- Based on the 2020 workshop, a briefing has been developed identifying salient human rights issues associated with specific issues which could include inter alia the energy and digital transitions in Tanzania. to supplement the existing NBA and other business and human rights studies;
- Select state actors have received technical support on implementation of priority business and human rights issues identified. e.g. those identified in the NBA, 2020 workshop and thematic briefing;
- Lessons learned from the national dialogue process have been shared at relevant regional or international fora.

- An expert multi-stakeholder workshop (involving participants from government, businesses, civil society, academia, etc.) has been held at regional level to identify priority policy and practice actions to address the human rights implications of the energy transition in the Sub-Saharan African region;
- A policy briefing is published and disseminated that builds on the 2020 background paper and the expert multi-stakeholder workshop, documenting key recommendations for state, business and civil society actors to address the human rights implications of the energy transition in the region;
- Findings and recommendations have been presented in relevant regional or international fora.

- A scoping study has been undertaken that has included identification of key stakeholders and salient business and human rights issues for the country;
- The scoping study includes an overview of the status of policy and practice elements of the energy and digital transitions;
- Select relevant state. business and civil society actors have been engaged to foster their capacity on business and human rights (DCA will focus on civil society engagement through their complementary project).

- Project partners and/or other relevant stakeholders have published and disseminated analysis of legal and policy gaps in business and human rights. e.g.. an NBA. targeted policy recommendations for achieving responsible business conduct in the energy and digital transition or other sectors as relevant;
- Multi-stakeholder dialogue has been conducted addressing specific salient business and human rights issues for the country;
- Lessons learned from national dialogue in Ethiopia have been shared at relevant regional or international fora.
